07960nam a22007815i 9780774851688DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20072005xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807748516887 a10.59962/97807748516882doi  a(DE-B1597)662180  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aE78.C2.C615 2005eb 7aSOC0210002bisacsh04a305.40900aContact Zones :bAboriginal and Settler Women in Canada's Colonial Past /ced. by Katie Pickles, Myra Rutherdale. 1aVancouver ;aToronto : bUniversity of British Columbia Press, c[2007] 4c©2005  a1 online resource (320 p.) :b16 b&w photographs  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tDressing and Performing Bodies: Aboriginal Women, Imperial Eyes, and Betweenness -- tSewing for a Living: The Commodification of Métis Women’s Artistic Production -- tChampioning the Native: E. Pauline Johnson Rejects the Squaw -- tPerforming for “Imperial Eyes”: Bernice Loft and Ethel Brant Monture, Ontario, 1930s–60s -- tSpirited Subjects and Wounded Souls: Political Representations of an Im/moral Frontier -- tRegulating the Body: Domesticity, Sexuality, and Transgression -- tMetropolitan Knowledge, Colonial Practice, and Indigenous Womanhood: Missions in Nineteenth-Century British Columbia -- tCreating “Semi-Widows” and “Supernumerary Wives”: Prohibiting Polygamy in Prairie Canada’s Aboriginal Communities to 1900 -- tIntimate Surveillance: Indian Affairs, Colonization, and the Regulation of Aboriginal Women’s Sexuality -- tDomesticating Girls: The Sexual Regulation of Aboriginal and Working-Class Girls in Twentieth-Century Canada -- tBodies in Everyday Space: Colonized and Colonizing Women in Canadian Contact Zones -- tAboriginal Women on the Streets of Victoria: Rethinking Transgressive Sexuality during the Colonial Encounter -- t“She Was a Ragged Little Thing”: Missionaries, Embodiment, and Refashioning Aboriginal Womanhood in Northern Canada -- tBelonging – Out of Place: Women’s Travelling Stories from the Western Edge -- tThe Old and New on Parade: Mimesis, Queen Victoria, and Carnival Queens on Victoria Day in Interwar Victoria -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aContact Zones locates Canadian women's history within colonial and imperial systems. As both colonizer and colonized (sometimes even simultaneously), women were uniquely positioned at the axis of the colonial encounter -- the so-called "contact zone" -- between Aboriginals and newcomers. Some women were able to transgress the bounds of social expectation, while others reluctantly conformed to them. Aboriginal women such as E. Pauline Johnson, Bernice Loft, and Ethel Brant Monture shaped identities for themselves in both worlds. By recognizing the necessity to "perform," they enchanted and educated white audiences across Canada. On the other side of the coin, newcomers imposed increasing regulation on Aboriginal women's bodies. Missionaries, for example, preached the virtues of Christian conjugality over mixed-race and polygamous marriages, especially those that hadn't been ratified by the church. The Department of Indian Affairs agents withheld treaty payments or removed the children of Aboriginal women who did not "properly" perform their duties as wives and mothers. In short, Aboriginal women were expected to consent to moral, sexual, and marital rules that white women were already beginning to contest. Contact Zones draws upon a vast array of primary sources to provide insight into the ubiquity and persistence of colonial discourse, and to demonstrate how it ultimately was an embodied experience. Above all, it shows how the colonial enterprise was about embodied contacts. What bodies belonged inside the nation, who were outsiders, and who transgressed the rules --- these are the questions at the heart of this provocative book. Jean Barman's chapter from Contact Zones, "Aboriginal Women on the Streets of Victoria: Rethinking Transgressive Sexuality during the Colonial Encounter', won the award from the Canadian Committee on the History of Sexuality. Cecilia Morgan's "Performing for 'Imperial Eyes': Bernice Loft and Ethel Brant Monture, Ontario, 1930s-60s" from Contact Zones, was awarded the Hilda Neatby Prize in Canadian Women's History.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aIndian womenzCanadaxHistoryy19th century. 0aIndian womenzCanadaxHistoryy20th century. 0aIndian womenzCanadaxSocial conditionsy19th century. 0aIndian womenzCanadaxSocial conditionsy20th century. 0aWomen pioneerszCanadaxHistoryy19th century. 0aWomen pioneerszCanadaxHistoryy20th century. 0aWomen pioneerszCanadaxSocial conditionsy19th century. 0aWomen pioneerszCanadaxSocial conditionsy20th century. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / Native American Studies.2bisacsh1 aBarman, Jean, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrownlie, Robin Jarvis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarter, Sarah A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFiske, Jo-Anne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGerson, Carole, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMorgan, Cecilia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNewell, Dianne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPerry, Adele, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPickles, Katie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPickles, Katie, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 